This is a great concept with a superb finish. This will sound like a critique that has lost a lot of its meaning, given how often it's repeated on this site, but I have to say that I'm not particularly enthused by the journal entry, which reads like a convenient note-at-the-end explaining the core premise. On the one hand, it dispels the mystery surrounding the murders in a relatively uncompelling manner. On the other hand, it's well-written and alludes to some of the wider implications that DiFortune's actions have on reality. Ultimately, I don't really mind it because it's pretty understated and sets up the final line quite well.







